\topic{Trigonometry Review}

\section*{Trigonometry Review}

In our earlier discussion of functions, we skipped over the
trigonometric functions.  We return to them now to discuss both their
properties and their derivative rules.

\vspace{5mm}

The trigonometric functions are usually defined for students first
using triangles (recall the mnemonic device, ``SOHCAHTOA'').

\vspace{1in}

\newpage
\problem Use the 45/45 and 60/30 triangles to compute the sine and
cosine of these common angles.

\includegraphics[height=2.5in]{graphics/notes_01_45_45_triangle}
\hfill
\includegraphics[height=2.5in]{graphics/notes_01_30_60_triangle}

\vfill

\newpage

{\bf Extending Trigonometric Domains}

One difficulty with limiting ourselves to the triangle ratio
definition of the trig functions is that the possible angles are
limited to the range $\theta \in [0, \frac{\pi}{2}]$ radians or
$\theta \in [0, 90]$ degrees.


To remove this limitation, mathematicians extended the definition of
the trigonometric functions to a wider domain via the unit circle.

% There are two fundamental interpretations of the sine and cosine
% functions, from which all the other trigonometric functions are
% defined:
% \begin{itemize}
% \item the point on the unit circle versus an angle
% \item the traditional oscillating graphs   
% \end{itemize}

\includegraphics[height=3.5in]{graphics/notes_01_circle_with_angle}
\includegraphics[height=3.5in]{graphics/notes_01_empty_graph_sine}

\newpage
\problem How does the circle definition lead to the trigonometric
  identity $\ds \sin^2(\theta) + \cos^2(\theta) = 1$?
\vfill

\newpage

\problem Show how the circle and triangle definitions define the same
values in the first quadrant of the unit circle.

\includegraphics[height=3.5in]{graphics/notes_01_circle}

\vfill

It is useful to understand both definitions of trig functions (circle
and triangle) as sometimes one is more helpful than the other for a
particular task.

\topic{Sine and Cosine as Functions}

\subsection*{Sine and Cosine as Oscillating Functions}

Despite the geometric source of the trigonometric functions, they are
used more commonly in biology and many other sciences as because their
{\bf periodicity} and {\bf oscillatory shapes}.  For many cyclic
behaviours in nature, trigonometric functions are a natural first
choice for modeling.

\vfill

