\topic{Derivatives of Trigonometric Functions}

\section*{Derivatives of Trigonometric Functions}

Having covered the graphs and properties of trigonometric functions,
we can now review the derivative formulae for those same functions.

The derivation of the formulas for the derivatives of $\sin$ and
$\cos$ are an interesting study in both limits and trigonometric
identities.  For those who are interested, many such derivations can
be found on the web\footnote{For example,
  http://www.math.com/tables/derivatives/more/trig.htm\#sin}.
However, it is in some ways more useful to derive the formula in a
graphical manner.

\newpage
Below is a graph of $\sin(x)$.  Use the graph to sketch the graph of
its derivative.

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{graphics/notes_01_sine}
\end{center}

\vfill

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{graphics/notes_01_cos_axes}
\end{center}

\newpage

From this sketch, we have evidence (though not a proof) that \vsc
\begin{boxnote}
{\bf Theorem} 
$$\ds \diff \sin x = $$
\end{boxnote}

\newpage

Most students will also be familiar with the other derivative rules
for trig functions:

\begin{boxnote}
$$ \ds \diff \cos( x) = - \sin (x)$$
$$ \ds \diff \tan(x) = \sec^2 (x)$$
$$ \ds \diff \sec(x) = \sec(x)\tan(x)$$
$$ \ds \diff \csc(x) = -\csc(x)\cot(x)$$
$$ \ds \diff \cot(x) = -\csc^2(x)$$
\end{boxnote}

\newpage
\problem Prove the secant derivative rule, using the definition
  $\ds \sec(x)= \frac{1}{\cos(x)}$ and the other derivative rules. 

\vfill

\newpage

{\bf Question:} Find the derivative of $4 + 6 \cos(\pi x^2 + 1)$

\begin{enumerate}[(a)]
\item $4 - 6 \sin(\pi x^2 + 1) \cdot (2 \pi x)$ \\[2ex]
\item $- 6 \cos(\pi x^2 + 1) \cdot (2 \pi x)$ \\[2ex]
\item $- 6 \sin(\pi x^2 + 1) \cdot (2 \pi x)$ \\[2ex]
\item $-6 \sin(\pi x^2 + 1) \cdot (\pi x^2 + 1)$ \\[2ex]
\item $6 \sin(2 \pi x)$ 
\end{enumerate}

